--- title: Dark Mode --- # Dark Mode Dark mode should feel like a softer clinical workspace, not a black canvas. The
common failure mode is using `neutral-950` for large surfaces and then layering `neutral-900` / `neutral-800` cards on
top until the UI feels heavy, flat, and cold. ## Rules - Avoid `neutral-950` as the default large-surface background. -
Use layered dark surfaces with clear separation. - Keep borders visible enough for dense controls and tables. - Keep
muted text readable, especially in grids, forms, and helper text. - Preserve strong focus rings. In dark mode, white or
primary-400 focus treatment is acceptable if contrast is clear. - Do not use decorative gradients to make dark mode feel
richer. ## Recommended Surface Stack ```css .dark { --pvc-color-surface: var(--color-neutral-900);
--pvc-color-surface-muted: var(--color-neutral-800); --pvc-color-surface-raised: color-mix(in oklab,
var(--color-neutral-800) 82%, white); --pvc-color-border: var(--color-neutral-700); --pvc-color-border-strong:
var(--color-neutral-600); --pvc-color-text: var(--color-neutral-100); --pvc-color-text-muted: var(--color-neutral-400);
--pvc-color-focus: var(--color-primary-400); } ``` ## Component Checks Check dark mode for: - Page and preview
backgrounds. - Data-grid header, body, row hover, active cell, and sticky cell boundaries. - Form labels, help text,
control borders, disabled controls, and checked states. - Button default, primary, danger, disabled, hover, and focus
states. - Tabs selected, hover, focus, lazy-loading, and error states. - Tooltips and code blocks, which may
intentionally use darker surfaces. ## Data Grid Note The data grid is the largest dense surface in Pathogen. It should
not become a solid `neutral-950` block by default. Header, body, row hover, borders, active cells, and scroll cues
should read as layered parts of the same product surface.
